snippet.textDisplay:
The difference between Son's incident and Maguire is that Maguire was sliding backwards (as opposed to forward) quite a distance while falling. In addition at the latter fall of the slide, the field switches to an incline as opposes to a flat surface.

The incline is only visible when seen from a specific low angle from a camera opposite of the bench side. When you see it from angle from the same side of the bench, its harder to see the incline and it just looks flat. Batshuayi's distance to him wasn't even constant.

Is there a chance that Maguire purposely intended to kick him out of spite? Yes, but the combined factors: direction of slide, speed of slide, change in relative distance to Batshuayi, and inclined surface gives him enough mitigating circumstances to give him the benefit of the doubt that it was a reaction to the fall.

Red cards can only be given when you are 100% certain and in addition this is a subjective incident which is supposed to have a high bar for VAR. If this was slower moving on a flat surface, then there would be more of a case againts him.

snippet.textDisplay: Harry Maguire couldn't have been sent off because it was a foul by Mitchy Batshuayi. Effectively the play was over when Batshuayi pushed Maguire and anything that happens afterwards shouldn't happen because ref should have blown his whistle and stopped the play. Now, VAR only checks obvious red cards. It was an obvious red card had Maguire gone down naturally but he went down due to a push by Batshuayi and that cancels out anything that happens afterwards. snippet.textDisplay:
and this is exactly why no EPL officials were allowed anywhere near WC2018....

90% of the poor calls made in this match benefited MU
maguire's is a game changer, because he scored 2nd goal and he shouldnt have been on the pitch.
william's is another game changer, because he was fouled in the box, so a PK should have been the result.
martial elbowing christensen in the face, another possible game changer as he scored 1st goal for MU.
while you could make the case it was an accident, in the replay you could clearly see him thrust his arm back a couple inches further, not much, but enough to make it "questionable" since it put his elbow in line with christensen's face...
zouma's goal should have been allowed as it was plain as day azpilicueta was pushed from behind, even the commentators stopped trying to make excuses by this point of the game and just openly questioned the officials.

I know there are more, I just believe those 3 calls changed the game dramatically.
at least they got giroud's offside call correct...
